</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[96,1533,742,884]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
The two members of this group are similar but can be separated by the stripes on the carapace of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Otto &amp; Hill 2012 c" authorityYear="2012" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maratus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velutinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">M. velutinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males of both species have a velvety-black fan with elongated, black dorsal scales (or 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">squamous setae</emphasis>
after 
<bibRefCitation author="Waldock" box="[245,444,818,847]" firstAuthor="Waldock" journalOrPublisher="Records of the Western Australian Museum" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="144 - 150" part="30" refId="ref11721" refString="Waldock, J. M. 2015. A new species of peacock spider, Maratus proszynskii sp. nov. (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryini), from Tasmania, with a review of Maratus in Tasmania, Australia. Records of the Western Australian Museum 30: 144 - 150." title="A new species of peacock spider, Maratus proszynskii sp. nov. (Araneae: Salticidae: Euophryini), from Tasmania, with a review of Maratus in Tasmania, Australia" type="journal article" year="2015">Waldock 2015</bibRefCitation>
) that extend to the rear. The fan is raised and moved from side to side but they do not raise legs III as they display to females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
